<!-- Compassionate Co-Learning Section -->
<section class="section colearning-section" id="colearning">
  <div class="container">
    <header class="section-header">
      <h2 class="section-title">Compassionate Co-Learning</h2>
      <span class="section-subtitle">how I teach</span>
    </header>

    <div class="colearning-layout">
      <div class="colearning-main">
        <p class="colearning-lead">The hardest part of learning to work with AI isn&rsquo;t technical. It&rsquo;s changing how you think about what you&rsquo;re capable of.</p>

        <p>I&rsquo;m trained in acceptance and commitment therapy, and I&rsquo;ve spent years as a coach and mindfulness mentor. The pattern is always the same: people don&rsquo;t resist change because they lack skill. They resist because shifting a paradigm means sitting with discomfort &mdash; and our instinct is to avoid discomfort, not move through it.</p>

        <p>In the labs, I watch it happen every cohort. Week one: &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t code.&rdquo; Week four: participants ship working products. This isn&rsquo;t informative learning &mdash; acquiring new skills on top of old assumptions. It&rsquo;s <em>transformative</em> learning. The underlying mindset changes.</p>

        <div class="colearning-progression">
          <div class="progression-step">
            <span class="progression-marker"></span>
            <div class="progression-content">
              <strong>Fear &amp; barrier</strong>
              <span>&ldquo;What scared me seemed like an obstacle&rdquo;</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="progression-step">
            <span class="progression-marker"></span>
            <div class="progression-content">
              <strong>Possibility</strong>
              <span>&ldquo;With this tool, it became possible not to be afraid&rdquo;</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="progression-step">
            <span class="progression-marker"></span>
            <div class="progression-content">
              <strong>Paradigm shift</strong>
              <span>&ldquo;My entire perception has shifted&rdquo;</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="progression-step">
            <span class="progression-marker"></span>
            <div class="progression-content">
              <strong>No boundaries</strong>
              <span>&ldquo;There&rsquo;s simply nothing that can&rsquo;t be done&rdquo;</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p>Psychological flexibility &mdash; ACT&rsquo;s core concept &mdash; turns out to be the exact skill you need for the agentic future. Notice what&rsquo;s happening without fusing with it. Accept uncertainty instead of demanding control. Take values-aligned action even when you&rsquo;re not sure it will work. The same framework that helps people live fuller lives helps them learn to coexist with autonomous systems.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="colearning-sidebar">
        <div class="colearning-principles">
          <h4>Lab principles</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Culture of error</strong> &mdash; mistakes are data, not failures. Every broken prototype teaches something a working one can&rsquo;t.</li>
            <li><strong>Complexity, not chaos</strong> &mdash; growth happens in the discomfort zone. Too easy = stagnation. Too hard = shutdown. I calibrate the edge.</li>
            <li><strong>Action over theory</strong> &mdash; you build from week one. The speed of going from thought to action is itself transformative.</li>
            <li><strong>Universal positive regard</strong> &mdash; every participant&rsquo;s path is valid. No &ldquo;right&rdquo; way to relate to AI &mdash; only your way, examined honestly.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="colearning-quote">
          <blockquote>
            &ldquo;Claude complemented this side of my brain, my personality, and it works super well.&rdquo;
            <cite>&mdash; Dmitry, product manager</cite>
          </blockquote>
          <blockquote>
            &ldquo;The state of flow, when you&rsquo;re constantly building &mdash; Claude Code brought that back into my life.&rdquo;
            <cite>&mdash; Alexander, investment analyst</cite>
